Narrative:
On May [XXX], 2025 at 8:00 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV came to a stop facing westbound on [XXX] at a stop sign at the intersection at [XXX] in a location where vegetation to the left of the AV created occlusion of the approaching near-side sidewalk. After coming to a stop at the stop line, the Waymo AV began moving forward into the intersection at [XXX] when a cyclist that had been traveling northwest on the near-side sidewalk along [XXX] entered the crosswalk and the front tire of the bike made contact with the front driver side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist fell to the ground.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The cyclist later informed Waymo of a minor injury.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On March [XXX], 2025 at 7:26 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southeastbound on [XXX] when it came to a stop at the stop sign at the intersection at [XXX]. While the Waymo AV was stopped, a passenger car approached the Waymo AV from behind, and the front of the passenger car made contact with the rear of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On March [XXX], 2025 at 7:08 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].

As the Waymo AV approached the intersection, a passenger car in the lane to the left of the Waymo AV changed lanes into the right lane without a turn signal activated, and the passenger side of the passenger car made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV. Cruise submits this updated report to add that the driver of the Chrysler PT Cruiser later claimed injuries related to the event. There are no other changes to Cruise's previous submission. On June [XXX], 2024 at 4:55AM MT, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode with three Cruise AV test operators onboard was traveling southbound on [XXX] in [XXX], Arizona when it approached a red light at the intersection with [XXX]. As the AV was stopping at the red light, a Chrysler PT Cruiser approached the AV from the rear but failed to stop and struck the rear of the nearly-stopped AV, causing severe damage to the Cruise AV and damage to the Chrysler PT Cruiser. The impact of the collision pushed the AV into the center of the intersection before the pair came to a stop. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called and came to the scene. The three Cruise AV test operators reported minor injuries. No parties were transported to the hospital from the scene of the collision, but the three AVTOs were later examined at a health care facility. The Cruise AV was towed from the scene.

On Tuesday, March [XXX], a Nuro Prius vehicle operating in manual was turning left from [XXX] onto [XXX] in Mountain View, California. This incident occurred near Streetman, TX on [XXX] at approximately 3:03 PM CT on February [XXX], 2024. The Aurora vehicle was operating in autonomy at the time. Conditions were clear. As the Aurora vehicle was driving in its lane at 62 mph, a box truck veered into the lane of the Aurora vehicle. The box truck's mirror appeared to make contact with the back of the trailer that the Aurora Driver was pulling. At this time, we are not aware of any injuries, and camera footage appears to show that the box truck continued to drive. From the post-trip inspection, there was not any visible trailer damage. Before the collision, the Aurora Driver was driving straight in its lane and passing the box truck. Shortly thereafter, the box truck began to encroach into the lane of the Aurora Driver. The Aurora Driver detected the box truck's encroachment into the Aurora vehicle's lane and initiated a nudge away from the box truck to provide space. The Aurora Driver detected the collision and made the decision to initiate an incident response, but before it could execute that response, the Vehicle Operator took over control of the system and proceeded in manual. The Aurora vehicle then re-engaged in autonomy approximately two minutes later. 
The Vehicle Operator did not visually observe the collision, assumed the reaction of the Aurora Driver to be a software anomaly, and reported the vehicle nudge through the standard annotation protocol rather than through the incident response protocols. The incident was identified at approximately 1:03 PM CT on February 2, 2024, through a review of Aurora's data logs.

While the light was still red, our vehicle slowly moved forward and then yielded for incoming cross traffic. On December [XXX], 2022, a Navya ARMA shuttle operated by Beep (VIN 1N9A1SACXJS[XXX]) was involved in a non-injury collision while operating in manual mode on [XXX] in Port Saint Lucie, FL.  While driving along [XXX] under autonomous control, the shuttle encountered a parked vehicle partially blocking its path, requiring disengagement of the autonomous drive system.  The safety driver attempted to manually drive the shuttle around the parked vehicle to reengage the autonomous drive system.  While manually steering the shuttle around the parked vehicle blocking its path, the shuttle failed to respond to manual control input and steered to the left, impacting a parked vehicle at a low rate of speed on the opposite side of [XXX].  The six passengers onboard alighted the shuttle, an accident report was filed with the local police, and the shuttle was removed from the scene.  Initial reports from the onboard safety driver indicated that while steering around the vehicle blocking the shuttle's path, the shuttle became unresponsive to control input.  The safety driver released the operator present button on the vehicle controller, which serves as dead man switch however, the vehicle failed to stop.  After the incident, further investigation by Navya confirmed that the root cause of the incident was a failure of the Xbox 360 controller used to manually control the vehicle.  Contact with the parked vehicle occurred between the time of failure and the vehicle drive system recognizing that the controller had failed an elapsed time of 4.05 seconds. In response to the incident, Beep suspended operation of all Navya ARMA vehicles pending identification and implementation of appropriate solutions to mitigate the risk of this failure leading to future incidents.
Subsequent investigation by Beep and Navya determined that the vehicle control software, NavyaDrive, is limited in its ability to monitor the validity of control signal input received from the Xbox 360 controller.  As the safety driver began to manually steer the vehicle, the controller failed, sending constant turning input to the vehicle drive system leading to the collision.  Though Navya developed software mitigations due to prior issues encountered with the controller, those mitigations were ineffective with respect to the failure leading to the incident on December [XXX].  Further, due to the short time between the controller failing and the collision (2.34sec), the safety driver was unable to identify the controller failure and trigger the emergency stop before the collision occurred.
In response to the incident, Navya is integrating a revised manual control system on the ARMA shuttle platform.  The revised manual control system utilizes industrial-grade components for improved electromechanical reliability and allows for active monitoring of the control system health, eliminating the root cause of the failure that led to the incident on December [XXX].  Software upgrades of all Navya ARMA vehicles will further reintroduce automated braking function while the ARMA vehicle is under manual control.  Beep is working with Navya to retrofit its fleet of ARMA vehicles with the revised manual control system as well as retrain and recertify its safety driver staff on the updated NavyaDrive software.
Discussion of the root cause analysis and solution design for the revised manual control system will be provided to NHTSA as a supplement to this report.

On September [XXX], 2022 at 6:38 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] and [XXX].
While traveling northbound on [XXX], the Waymo AV changed lanes from the center lane to the right lane before slowing to a stop at a red light at [XXX].  While the Waymo AV was making the lane change, the vehicle immediately behind the Waymo AV in the right lane moved to the center lane and made contact with the right rear sensor of the Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position).  The SUV sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of WaymoLLC-20220917-0 (rev.20221017214905).

On August [XXX], 2022 at 6:33 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") Peterbilt Class 8 semi-truck and trailer, operating in Ennis, Texas was in a collision involving a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer on northbound [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in autonomous mode in the middle lane on [XXX] when a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer began to pass it in the adjacent left lane.  Before the adjacent Class 8 semi-truck and trailer had fully passed the Waymo AV, it began to execute a right lane change and its trailer (the right side, rear section) entered the lane in which the Waymo AV was traveling and made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV cab.  The Waymo AV transitioned to manual mode and the test driver took control.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position).  The Waymo AV sustained damage and the third-party Class 8 semi-truck and trailer did not stop to exchange information.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of WaymoLLC-202208[XXX]-0 (rev. 2022019[XXX]185808)

On February [XXX], 2022 at 5:46 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and traveling southbound on [XXX] when it came to a stop at [XXX]. As the Waymo AV proceeded, a bicyclist traveling northbound on [XXX] proceeded through the stop sign without stopping in order to make a left turn onto westbound [XXX]. The Waymo AV began to brake and the test driver (in the driver's seating position), disengaged the AV system and continued braking. As the bicyclist attempted to complete their left turn, the bicyclist made contact with the driver side rear corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.
